div.p:
In computer science, string interning is a method of storing only one copy of each distinct string value, which must be immutable.[1]
Interning strings makes some string processing tasks more time- or
space-efficient at the cost of requiring more time when the string is
created or interned. The distinct values are stored in a string intern pool

library/ contains the standard libraries (core, alloc, std,
proc_macro, test), as well as the Rust runtime (backtrace, rtstartup,
lang_start).

src/ contains the source code for rustdoc, clippy, cargo, the build system,
language docs, etc.
